  title="How Often Should You Get Your Chimney Cleaned in Melbourne?"
  description="The short answer is once a year — but the right frequency for your Melbourne home depends on how often you use it and what you're burning. Here's the full guide."
  publishDate="April 2026"
  readTime="5 min"
>
  <p>The most common question Dave gets asked when he shows up for a job is some version of: <strong>"How often should I actually be getting this done?"</strong> It's a fair question — chimney sweeping isn't something that comes with a sticker on the fridge reminding you it's due.</p>

  <p>Here's the straightforward answer for Melbourne households.</p>

  <h2>The Standard Recommendation: Once a Year</h2>

  <p>For a fireplace or wood heater that gets regular use through a Melbourne winter, <strong>once a year is the standard</strong>. This is consistent with the advice from fire safety authorities across Victoria and aligns with what most chimney professionals in Melbourne recommend.</p>

  <p>Annual cleaning prevents dangerous creosote buildup, keeps the flue clear of blockages, and gives you a chance to catch any structural issues before they become expensive problems.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>The ideal time to book is <strong>late summer or early autumn</strong> — before the cold hits and before every chimney sweep in Melbourne is booked out. April and May are the sweet spot.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>When You Should Be Getting It Done More Often</h2>

  <p>Some situations call for more frequent cleaning than once a year:</p>

  <h3>You burn a lot of wood</h3>
  <p>If your fire is running five or six nights a week from May through September, you're generating significantly more creosote than a household that uses it occasionally. Heavy users — say, more than 3–4 cords of wood per season — should consider cleaning twice a year.</p>

  <h3>You're burning green or unseasoned wood</h3>
  <p>Unseasoned wood (wood that hasn't been properly dried) produces far more creosote than well-seasoned hardwood. If you've been burning green wood, you need to get your chimney checked regardless of when it was last cleaned.</p>

  <h3>You've noticed performance issues</h3>
  <p>Smoke coming back into the room, a sluggish fire, or a persistent smell of smoke when the fire isn't burning are all signs of a blocked or restricted flue — and that means it needs attention now, not at the end of winter.</p>

  <h3>The chimney hasn't been cleaned in several years</h3>
  <p>If you've moved into a home and have no idea when the chimney was last swept — or if it's been more than two or three years — get it done immediately. Creosote can build up to dangerous levels without any obvious symptoms.</p>

  <h2>When Once Every Two Years Might Be Fine</h2>

  <p>If you use your fireplace very occasionally — a few times over winter, burning only well-seasoned hardwood — then stretching to every 18 months or two years is probably acceptable. That said, an annual inspection even without a full clean is still worthwhile to check for blockages and structural issues.</p>

  <p>Open fireplaces that are largely decorative and barely used can get away with less frequent sweeping. But if you can't remember the last time it was done, that's your answer: it needs doing now.</p>

  <h2>What About New Homes or First-Time Owners?</h2>

  <p>If you've just bought a property with a fireplace or wood heater, get the chimney inspected before you use it — even if the house is relatively new or was recently sold. A home inspection doesn't always include a detailed chimney assessment, and blockages, bird nests or structural damage aren't visible without looking up the flue.</p>

  <h2>Melbourne's Climate Makes Annual Cleaning Particularly Important</h2>

  <p>Melbourne's winters are cold enough that wood heaters and fireplaces get a serious workout from May through August. The start of autumn — when most households are thinking about lighting the fire for the first time — is exactly when you want to know the chimney is clean and clear, not after the first smoky evening when you realise something's wrong.</p>

  <p>An annual clean in March or April means your fire is ready to go the moment you need it.</p>
